>>LISA: Welcome back to
"Gaiam Inspirations."

00:26:12.570 --> 00:26:13.590 align:middle line:90%
I'm Lisa Garr.

00:26:13.590 --> 00:26:15.630 align:middle line:90%
And my guest is Riane Eisler.

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:18.297 align:middle line:84%
She is a social scientist
and an amazing woman.

00:26:18.297 --> 00:26:19.880 align:middle line:84%
We've been having a
great conversation

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:22.480 align:middle line:84%
about gender and
gender equality.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:25.765 align:middle line:84%
Why is it so important to have
this conversation about gender?

00:26:25.765 --> 00:26:27.570 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, we've
been taught, really,

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:31.735 align:middle line:84%
that anything to do with gender
is just a women's issue, which

00:26:31.735 --> 00:26:34.110 align:middle line:84%
is kind of ridiculous because
we're half of humanity.

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:35.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I'm glad you said that.

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:35.530 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:26:35.530 --> 00:26:38.460 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But the
reality is if you really

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.610 align:middle line:84%
look at the whole of
a social system, which

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:48.440 align:middle line:84%
is what my research does, we see
that how a society constructs

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:51.900 align:middle line:84%
the roles and relations of
these two halves of humanity--

00:26:51.900 --> 00:26:54.670 align:middle line:84%
which is what women
and men are-- not only

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:58.430 align:middle line:84%
affects directly our life
choices as women and men,

00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:00.860 align:middle line:84%
as girls and boys,
but that it affects

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:02.990 align:middle line:90%
everything about the system.

00:27:02.990 --> 00:27:04.350 align:middle line:90%
Our beliefs.

00:27:04.350 --> 00:27:08.300 align:middle line:84%
What we are told is
valuable or not valuable.

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:10.640 align:middle line:84%
All of our institutions,
from the family--

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:16.480 align:middle line:84%
whether it's authoritarian more
democratic-- religion, media,

00:27:16.480 --> 00:27:19.280 align:middle line:90%
politics, and economics.

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:22.630 align:middle line:84%
And in my last book, "The
Real Wealth of Nations,"

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:27.920 align:middle line:84%
one of the things that comes
to the fore again and again

00:27:27.920 --> 00:27:33.550 align:middle line:84%
is that the reason, really the
underlying reason that there

00:27:33.550 --> 00:27:37.210 align:middle line:84%
always seems to be
enough money for prisons,

00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:39.875 align:middle line:84%
to punish, for wars,
and weapons to conquer--

00:27:39.875 --> 00:27:41.125 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's never questioned.

00:27:41.125 --> 00:27:44.240 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But there never seems
to be enough money for caring

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:47.950 align:middle line:84%
for people, for health
care, for child care,

00:27:47.950 --> 00:27:51.790 align:middle line:84%
for paid parental leave-- is
because, in the domination

00:27:51.790 --> 00:27:55.470 align:middle line:84%
system, men are
ranked over women.

00:27:55.470 --> 00:27:58.740 align:middle line:84%
And anything
stereotypically considered

00:27:58.740 --> 00:28:03.020 align:middle line:84%
feminine, such as caring,
caregiving, nonviolence,

00:28:03.020 --> 00:28:07.270 align:middle line:84%
is also devalued, whether
it's in a woman or a man.

00:28:07.270 --> 00:28:09.900 align:middle line:84%
So men are wimps, they're
sissies, they're effeminate.

00:28:09.900 --> 00:28:12.660 align:middle line:84%
I mean, why should
effeminate be a pejorative?

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:16.800 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is that unless
we see this hidden subtext

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:21.770 align:middle line:84%
of gendered values, we
can't make sense of things.

00:28:21.770 --> 00:28:24.440 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the most
important investment

00:28:24.440 --> 00:28:27.890 align:middle line:84%
as we move into the
post-industrial knowledge

00:28:27.890 --> 00:28:32.320 align:middle line:84%
service economy is what
economists keep telling us.

00:28:32.320 --> 00:28:36.490 align:middle line:84%
It is what they like to call
high quality human capital--

00:28:36.490 --> 00:28:41.910 align:middle line:84%
flexible, creative people
who can solve problems.

00:28:41.910 --> 00:28:45.260 align:middle line:84%
That does not just
happen in universities.

00:28:45.260 --> 00:28:48.800 align:middle line:84%
We know from neuroscience
that the most important time

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:53.280 align:middle line:84%
for that to either happen
or not as our brains develop

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:55.530 align:middle line:90%
is in early childhood care.

00:28:55.530 --> 00:29:00.000 align:middle line:84%
So if we are really to do what
every other industrialized and

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.730 align:middle line:84%
now post-industrial
nation is doing,

00:29:02.730 --> 00:29:06.650 align:middle line:84%
invest in paid parental leave
for both mothers and fathers.

00:29:06.650 --> 00:29:08.740 align:middle line:90%
Government funded.

00:29:08.740 --> 00:29:12.730 align:middle line:84%
Invest in high quality
early childhood education.

00:29:12.730 --> 00:29:19.505 align:middle line:84%
The return on investment, the
studies show, on this is 200%.

00:29:19.505 --> 00:29:21.726 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Return on investment
for any corporation that

00:29:21.726 --> 00:29:23.100 align:middle line:84%
supports that type
of child care.

00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:24.890 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: For any government
that supports that child care.

00:29:24.890 --> 00:29:26.223 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's very interesting.

00:29:26.223 --> 00:29:27.810 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And we're
today being told

00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:30.320 align:middle line:84%
that these are precisely
what we need to cut.

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:33.250 align:middle line:90%
Well we will not be competitive.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:36.690 align:middle line:84%
We will not be competitive
in the new economy.

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:39.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is not only a question
of doing what's right.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:43.600 align:middle line:84%
It's a question of not
committing economic suicide.

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:48.050 align:middle line:84%
And that's really why we so need
what I call a Caring Economy.

00:29:48.050 --> 00:29:50.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, this--
actually, this next clip

00:29:50.040 --> 00:29:51.990 align:middle line:84%
shows the difference
between gender,

00:29:51.990 --> 00:29:56.464 align:middle line:84%
and how there is such a wide
gap where it comes to care,

00:29:56.464 --> 00:29:57.630 align:middle line:90%
when it comes to child care.

00:29:57.630 --> 00:29:58.645 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:29:58.645 --> 00:30:00.505 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:00.505 --> 00:30:05.600 align:middle line:84%
- Re-examining and
changing the valuations,

00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:11.440 align:middle line:84%
the values that today
drive economic systems.

00:30:11.440 --> 00:30:13.770 align:middle line:84%
Now of course
economics really is

00:30:13.770 --> 00:30:16.380 align:middle line:90%
about what is or is not valued.

00:30:16.380 --> 00:30:19.270 align:middle line:84%
And classical economists
will tell you, yeah,

00:30:19.270 --> 00:30:23.660 align:middle line:84%
but that is determined
by supply and demand.

00:30:23.660 --> 00:30:25.390 align:middle line:90%
And that is part of it.

00:30:25.390 --> 00:30:31.540 align:middle line:84%
But much more important are
the underlying cultural values,

00:30:31.540 --> 00:30:35.100 align:middle line:84%
values that are so
unconsciously embedded

00:30:35.100 --> 00:30:38.180 align:middle line:84%
that we're often not
even aware of them.

00:30:38.180 --> 00:30:40.830 align:middle line:90%
Let me give you an example.

00:30:40.830 --> 00:30:45.320 align:middle line:84%
Professions that do not entail
caring and caregiving-- they

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:47.470 align:middle line:84%
can be done by caring
people, but the work

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:49.400 align:middle line:90%
is not caregiving work.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:50.460 align:middle line:90%
Engineering.

00:30:50.460 --> 00:30:52.180 align:middle line:90%
Plumbing.

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:56.360 align:middle line:84%
They are much higher paid than
those professions that do,

00:30:56.360 --> 00:31:00.530 align:middle line:84%
such as child care,
elementary school teaching.

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:03.640 align:middle line:84%
So in the United
States, people think

00:31:03.640 --> 00:31:07.510 align:middle line:84%
nothing of paying the plumber--
the person to whom we entrust

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:11.940 align:middle line:90%
our pipes-- $50 to $100 an hour.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:14.920 align:middle line:84%
But the child care
worker-- the person

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:18.010 align:middle line:84%
to whom we entrust our
children-- according

00:31:18.010 --> 00:31:21.930 align:middle line:84%
to the US Department of
Labor, gets an average

00:31:21.930 --> 00:31:26.140 align:middle line:84%
of less than $10 an
hour with no benefits.

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:27.730 align:middle line:84%
And of course we
insist plumbers be

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:32.370 align:middle line:84%
trained, but not that child
care workers be trained.

00:31:32.370 --> 00:31:35.040 align:middle line:90%
Now this is not logical.

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:38.290 align:middle line:90%
It's actually pathological.

00:31:38.290 --> 00:31:40.277 align:middle line:90%
And we've got to change it.

00:31:40.277 --> 00:31:41.110 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:31:41.110 --> 00:31:42.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:31:42.410 --> 00:31:44.210 align:middle line:84%
We have to find a
way to change that.

00:31:44.210 --> 00:31:46.090 align:middle line:84%
And that is what you're
talking about today--

00:31:46.090 --> 00:31:48.340 align:middle line:84%
is finding ways to
change that into more

00:31:48.340 --> 00:31:51.110 align:middle line:84%
of an inclusive
partnership model.

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:53.240 align:middle line:84%
One of the listeners
actually is asking--

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:54.960 align:middle line:90%
this is a great question.

00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Jan from Facebook is
saying, "how do you

00:31:56.930 --> 00:32:00.190 align:middle line:84%
teach children to
deal with the images

00:32:00.190 --> 00:32:04.720 align:middle line:84%
on TV that are being given
of females on television?"

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:05.870 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

00:32:05.870 --> 00:32:09.870 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: That's really
part of the regression

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:14.480 align:middle line:84%
to the domination side of the
continuum that we're seeing it.

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:18.630 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's not new
to objectify women.

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:19.700 align:middle line:90%
It goes way back.

00:32:19.700 --> 00:32:25.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you look at Greek
vases and et cetera.

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:29.340 align:middle line:84%
But what is new is the
explicit sexuality.

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:31.366 align:middle line:84%
Now there's nothing
wrong with sex.

00:32:31.366 --> 00:32:32.990 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I wrote a
whole book about that

00:32:32.990 --> 00:32:35.230 align:middle line:90%
called "Sacred Pleasure."

00:32:35.230 --> 00:32:40.970 align:middle line:84%
But it is really the erotization
of domination and violence

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:43.760 align:middle line:90%
that's wrong with sex.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:45.622 align:middle line:84%
And that's our
dominator heritage.

00:32:45.622 --> 00:32:51.050 align:middle line:84%
I mean, one way of
really getting a hold

00:32:51.050 --> 00:32:53.610 align:middle line:84%
of people's-- because sex is a
very important part of life--

00:32:53.610 --> 00:32:55.500 align:middle line:90%
is to say sex is bad.

00:32:55.500 --> 00:32:56.670 align:middle line:90%
And women are temptresses.

00:32:56.670 --> 00:32:57.170 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:32:57.170 --> 00:32:57.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:32:57.300 --> 00:32:58.730 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --you
know, that thing.

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:02.710 align:middle line:84%
But the other way is what we
see so much in the media today,

00:33:02.710 --> 00:33:06.770 align:middle line:84%
constant linking of sex with
domination and with violence

00:33:06.770 --> 00:33:09.470 align:middle line:84%
and with the
objectification of women

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:11.605 align:middle line:84%
as just a sex object,
not a human being.

00:33:11.605 --> 00:33:12.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It does
seem like there's

00:33:12.980 --> 00:33:14.930 align:middle line:84%
a new line that has
been crossed, however,

00:33:14.930 --> 00:33:18.240 align:middle line:90%
that just keeps getting pushed.

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:20.440 align:middle line:84%
I have a young
child, a young girl.

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:22.340 align:middle line:84%
And I am trying
to figure out how

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:26.130 align:middle line:84%
to teach her to handle those
images that are coming at her.

00:33:26.130 --> 00:33:28.830 align:middle line:84%
No matter-- there's no
shielding a child from that.

00:33:28.830 --> 00:33:31.880 align:middle line:84%
You drive to school, and
there's 37 billboards

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:37.030 align:middle line:84%
of ladies that are--
barely have any clothes on.

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:39.400 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And that's a
complete objectification.

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:40.650 align:middle line:90%
And it's totally unrealistic.

00:33:40.650 --> 00:33:43.960 align:middle line:84%
There's a wonderful
magazine for girls

00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:48.540 align:middle line:84%
that is published by a company
called-- it's called New Moon.

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:52.410 align:middle line:84%
And it's written
and edited by girls.

00:33:52.410 --> 00:33:54.040 align:middle line:90%
And I highly recommend it.

00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:56.180 align:middle line:84%
I've given it always
to my granddaughters

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:57.190 align:middle line:90%
and to other girls.

00:33:57.190 --> 00:33:58.398 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: But what does it say?

00:33:58.398 --> 00:33:59.310 align:middle line:90%
What do I say to her?

00:33:59.310 --> 00:34:00.850 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: What do
you say to her?

00:34:00.850 --> 00:34:06.240 align:middle line:84%
You tell her that that
is a way that women

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:08.760 align:middle line:84%
have been viewed
for a long time.

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:12.190 align:middle line:84%
And that we really think
it's very unhealthy.

00:34:12.190 --> 00:34:15.750 align:middle line:84%
That you are much more
than your body parts.

00:34:15.750 --> 00:34:17.770 align:middle line:84%
Your body parts have
to be respected.

00:34:17.770 --> 00:34:19.800 align:middle line:84%
Whether somebody
sees them or not

00:34:19.800 --> 00:34:22.630 align:middle line:84%
is something that you
have to determine,

00:34:22.630 --> 00:34:24.139 align:middle line:90%
whether somebody touches them.

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:25.489 align:middle line:90%
We need sex education.

00:34:25.489 --> 00:34:26.781 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:34:26.781 --> 00:34:27.280 align:middle line:90%
A lot more.

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:28.025 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: A lot more.

00:34:28.025 --> 00:34:29.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it's got
to start at home, really.

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:30.974 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It's got
to start at home.

00:34:30.974 --> 00:34:31.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:33.239 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to come
from an institution.

00:34:33.239 --> 00:34:33.780 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: No.

00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:36.889 align:middle line:84%
But we need to also have
it in the institutions.

00:34:36.889 --> 00:34:42.310 align:middle line:84%
Because not all parents are
able to really deal with it.

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:46.080 align:middle line:84%
They'd rather have their kids
watch violence on television

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:50.520 align:middle line:84%
than sex, which I think, I
mean, doesn't make much sense.

00:34:50.520 --> 00:34:53.449 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But it also has to do
with what you're talking about,

00:34:53.449 --> 00:34:55.770 align:middle line:84%
our social conditioning
around all of this.

00:34:55.770 --> 00:34:59.100 align:middle line:84%
Because this has now
become socially acceptable.

00:34:59.100 --> 00:34:59.800 align:middle line:90%
It's the norm.

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:02.070 align:middle line:84%
It's the domination
model once again.

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:04.580 align:middle line:84%
So how do we educate
ourselves in order

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:05.935 align:middle line:90%
to educate our children?

00:35:05.935 --> 00:35:07.830 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, we
educate ourselves

00:35:07.830 --> 00:35:10.030 align:middle line:84%
by looking at the
so-called sexual revolution

00:35:10.030 --> 00:35:13.090 align:middle line:84%
and understanding that there
were healthy parts to it.

00:35:13.090 --> 00:35:16.760 align:middle line:84%
The acceptance that sex is
a normal, pleasurable human

00:35:16.760 --> 00:35:17.890 align:middle line:90%
activity.

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:22.470 align:middle line:84%
But then the part that was
tainted by our domination

00:35:22.470 --> 00:35:25.336 align:middle line:84%
heritage is this notion
that women are now

00:35:25.336 --> 00:35:28.060 align:middle line:90%
to be just available for men.

00:35:28.060 --> 00:35:30.190 align:middle line:84%
That that's how they
get their status.

00:35:30.190 --> 00:35:31.657 align:middle line:90%
That's how-- it's the old model.

00:35:31.657 --> 00:35:32.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's going back to that.

00:35:32.990 --> 00:35:35.970 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It's
going back to that.

00:35:35.970 --> 00:35:39.810 align:middle line:84%
And unfortunately, the
sexualization of little girls

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:41.500 align:middle line:90%
has become a business.

00:35:41.500 --> 00:35:42.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, yes, it has.

00:35:42.500 --> 00:35:45.960 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Selling all of those
clothes and all of that stuff.

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:47.860 align:middle line:84%
Indoctrinating them
before their brains

00:35:47.860 --> 00:35:51.440 align:middle line:84%
are formed so they have
any critical faculties.

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:53.450 align:middle line:90%
So yes, we've got a job to do.

00:35:53.450 --> 00:35:55.909 align:middle line:84%
But I always want you to
understand something here.

00:35:55.909 --> 00:35:57.950 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's really
important for all of us

00:35:57.950 --> 00:35:58.920 align:middle line:90%
to understand.

00:35:58.920 --> 00:36:01.370 align:middle line:84%
There's always this tension
between the partnership

00:36:01.370 --> 00:36:03.450 align:middle line:90%
and domination trends.

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:06.640 align:middle line:84%
And we can strengthen the
partnership ones, for example,

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:09.250 align:middle line:84%
by using resources
like New Moon.

00:36:09.250 --> 00:36:11.470 align:middle line:84%
For example, by
insisting that there

00:36:11.470 --> 00:36:17.070 align:middle line:84%
be real sex education that
talks about caring commitment

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:20.090 align:middle line:84%
in a sexual relationship,
that teaches

00:36:20.090 --> 00:36:25.450 align:middle line:84%
both boys and girls that it's
not-- instant gratification

00:36:25.450 --> 00:36:28.080 align:middle line:84%
is not what's going
to make a happy life.

00:36:28.080 --> 00:36:29.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: In the long run.

00:36:29.260 --> 00:36:31.880 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if you tell
that to a young boy,

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:33.980 align:middle line:84%
they will tell you
that it-- I mean,

00:36:33.980 --> 00:36:36.130 align:middle line:84%
the social conditioning
is appealing

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:38.030 align:middle line:84%
to the rising hormones
in young boys.

00:36:38.030 --> 00:36:39.280 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: There's no question.

00:36:39.280 --> 00:36:41.100 align:middle line:84%
But the girls also have
those rising hormones.

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:42.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And, I was just
about to say, and girls.

00:36:42.670 --> 00:36:43.150 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:36:43.150 --> 00:36:43.530 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:36:43.530 --> 00:36:44.020 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: So.

00:36:44.020 --> 00:36:44.390 align:middle line:90%
But still.

00:36:44.390 --> 00:36:46.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So we have to teach
about the social conditioning,

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:47.165 align:middle line:90%
more so.

00:36:47.165 --> 00:36:48.040 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Absolutely.

00:36:48.040 --> 00:36:50.990 align:middle line:84%
I mean, is this really--
I mean, do you really

00:36:50.990 --> 00:36:54.999 align:middle line:84%
want that kind of a relationship
to both boys and girls?

00:36:54.999 --> 00:36:56.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's interesting
because it's real.

00:36:56.790 --> 00:36:57.927 align:middle line:90%
It is what is happening.

00:36:57.927 --> 00:36:59.260 align:middle line:90%
It's what is all over our media.

00:36:59.260 --> 00:37:00.718 align:middle line:84%
And it's exactly
what we're seeing.

00:37:00.718 --> 00:37:03.780 align:middle line:84%
So it kind of leads us into
the conversation of the action

00:37:03.780 --> 00:37:05.720 align:middle line:84%
plans that you
have and that have

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:08.740 align:middle line:84%
been created with
your organization.

00:37:08.740 --> 00:37:12.550 align:middle line:84%
As well as the Caring Economics,
there's six areas for action

00:37:12.550 --> 00:37:13.850 align:middle line:90%
that you propose.

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:14.830 align:middle line:90%
What are they?

00:37:14.830 --> 00:37:17.640 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, I think
the first thing, really,

00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:21.180 align:middle line:84%
is that we have
to re-examine what

00:37:21.180 --> 00:37:24.770 align:middle line:84%
is a healthy economic system,
to change the conversation.

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:27.370 align:middle line:84%
And yes, to start talking
about a caring economy.

00:37:27.370 --> 00:37:29.770 align:middle line:84%
And people are going
to say, caring?!

00:37:29.770 --> 00:37:30.650 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that soft--

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:31.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What is that?

00:37:31.620 --> 00:37:34.650 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --that soft fuzzy
feminine stuff, you know.

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:37.590 align:middle line:84%
They're going to say, well,
that's just not effective.

00:37:37.590 --> 00:37:42.920 align:middle line:84%
So the second thing is really to
show how very effective it is.

00:37:42.920 --> 00:37:46.400 align:middle line:84%
That companies that have
caring policies, companies

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:48.790 align:middle line:84%
that are regularly in the
Fortune 500 or the Working

00:37:48.790 --> 00:37:53.290 align:middle line:84%
Mothers-- companies as the best
companies to work for-- that

00:37:53.290 --> 00:37:55.480 align:middle line:84%
have caring policies,
that they have

00:37:55.480 --> 00:37:58.800 align:middle line:84%
a substantially higher
return to investors.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:37:59.880 align:middle line:90%
And it makes sense.

00:37:59.880 --> 00:38:01.921 align:middle line:84%
If people and their
families feel cared for--

00:38:01.921 --> 00:38:02.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:38:02.420 --> 00:38:03.300 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: They're
going to work very

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:04.660 align:middle line:84%
hard to make that
company successful.

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:06.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And they'll
want to keep that job.

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:07.816 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And we
also have to look

00:38:07.816 --> 00:38:12.100 align:middle line:84%
at nations that have been highly
successful-- in human terms

00:38:12.100 --> 00:38:15.010 align:middle line:84%
and in economic
terms-- in many ways,

00:38:15.010 --> 00:38:18.150 align:middle line:84%
much more successful than
this very rich United States.

00:38:18.150 --> 00:38:20.615 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You explain the Nordic
nations are very supportive.

00:38:20.615 --> 00:38:24.070 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Sweden, Finland,
Norway, Iceland, Denmark--

00:38:24.070 --> 00:38:26.760 align:middle line:84%
they all have more
caring policies.

00:38:26.760 --> 00:38:29.960 align:middle line:84%
And the thing-- They have paid
parental leave for both mothers

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:30.850 align:middle line:90%
and fathers.

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:32.730 align:middle line:90%
Universal health care.

00:38:32.730 --> 00:38:35.130 align:middle line:84%
They have high
quality child care.

00:38:35.130 --> 00:38:37.950 align:middle line:84%
Their kids, by the
way, score very high

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:40.710 align:middle line:90%
in tests, international tests.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:43.700 align:middle line:84%
And they have low poverty
and low crime rates

00:38:43.700 --> 00:38:46.250 align:middle line:84%
and a generally high
standard of living.

00:38:46.250 --> 00:38:49.020 align:middle line:84%
Everything that we
are not seeing here.

00:38:49.020 --> 00:38:51.880 align:middle line:84%
And they invested in
caring for their people.

00:38:51.880 --> 00:38:54.560 align:middle line:84%
And we come back
to gender again,

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:57.030 align:middle line:84%
which is another one
of these steps showing,

00:38:57.030 --> 00:39:01.270 align:middle line:90%
really, the gender connection.

00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:04.850 align:middle line:84%
It's only because the
status of women rose.

00:39:04.850 --> 00:39:08.150 align:middle line:84%
Because 40% of the national
legislature is female,

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:09.910 align:middle line:90%
say in Sweden, Finland, Norway--

00:39:09.910 --> 00:39:10.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:12.330 align:middle line:84%
Which is very
different from here.

00:39:12.330 --> 00:39:14.630 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --that not
only women, but also men

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:17.280 align:middle line:90%
voted for more caring policies.

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:19.105 align:middle line:84%
So they call themselves
caring societies.

00:39:19.105 --> 00:39:22.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You mentioned
that the females--

00:39:22.130 --> 00:39:24.469 align:middle line:84%
the mothers cannot get
the maternity leave unless

00:39:24.469 --> 00:39:26.010 align:middle line:84%
the fathers take
the paternity leave?

00:39:26.010 --> 00:39:31.050 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: In Sweden, if it's
a woman-man family, yes.

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:34.945 align:middle line:84%
If the father doesn't take
it, then neither gets it.

00:39:34.945 --> 00:39:36.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's interesting.

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:40.080 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, you see it
gives men the opportunity,

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:41.720 align:middle line:84%
doesn't it, that we
spoke of earlier--

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:42.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:39:42.270 --> 00:39:45.430 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --to the man who asked
the question about the child--

00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:46.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:39:46.130 --> 00:39:49.160 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --the father,
to really experience

00:39:49.160 --> 00:39:51.120 align:middle line:90%
that bonding, that pleasure.

00:39:51.120 --> 00:39:55.080 align:middle line:84%
Look, what we really want
for both women and men is

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:58.630 align:middle line:84%
that we can each express
all of our potentials,

00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:00.530 align:middle line:90%
that women can be leaders.

00:40:00.530 --> 00:40:03.690 align:middle line:84%
That they can be
assertive and not

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:05.787 align:middle line:84%
be called ball breakers,
or whatever, bitches.

00:40:05.787 --> 00:40:06.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:40:06.370 --> 00:40:06.869 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:40:06.869 --> 00:40:10.610 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And that men can
be caring and sensitive

00:40:10.610 --> 00:40:13.320 align:middle line:90%
and experience the joy of that.

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:13.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:16.602 align:middle line:84%
And we are establishing
new models all the time.

00:40:16.602 --> 00:40:18.060 align:middle line:84%
One of our listeners
here-- and I'm

00:40:18.060 --> 00:40:20.230 align:middle line:84%
encouraging your
questions via Facebook

00:40:20.230 --> 00:40:24.220 align:middle line:84%
and Twitter-- Lynn is asking--
she retired as a teacher.

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:25.890 align:middle line:84%
And she's saying
because she was fed up

00:40:25.890 --> 00:40:27.280 align:middle line:90%
with the education system.

00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:29.270 align:middle line:84%
And she wants to know
how she can really

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:31.550 align:middle line:90%
effect social change.

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:32.410 align:middle line:90%
How can she?

00:40:32.410 --> 00:40:34.470 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, first of
all, I don't blame her

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:36.790 align:middle line:84%
for being fed up
with this teaching

00:40:36.790 --> 00:40:39.540 align:middle line:84%
to the test, which is really
a regression to the domination

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:40.040 align:middle line:90%
system.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:42.534 align:middle line:90%
It's again the ranking.

00:40:42.534 --> 00:40:44.200 align:middle line:84%
Grading on tje curve
is the worst thing.

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:45.730 align:middle line:90%
Somebody has to fail.

00:40:45.730 --> 00:40:48.940 align:middle line:84%
And somebody has to be on top,
no matter how good you are.

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:50.149 align:middle line:90%
Somebody has to be on bottom.

00:40:50.149 --> 00:40:50.648 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:40:50.648 --> 00:40:52.920 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And that takes
away from what really counts,

00:40:52.920 --> 00:40:55.427 align:middle line:84%
which is the teacher's
engagement with the child--

00:40:55.427 --> 00:40:56.510 align:middle line:90%
engaging, being partners--

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:57.301 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Empowering.

00:40:57.301 --> 00:40:58.550 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: --with the child.

00:40:58.550 --> 00:40:59.650 align:middle line:90%
But how can she?

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:02.560 align:middle line:84%
Social change doesn't
happen by Itself.

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:06.940 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the European
Middle Ages, as I said,

00:41:06.940 --> 00:41:09.100 align:middle line:90%
they looked like the Taliban.

00:41:09.100 --> 00:41:12.600 align:middle line:84%
We moved, but it happened
through human agency.

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing is
changing the conversation.

00:41:14.990 --> 00:41:18.800 align:middle line:84%
The old terms for the more
rigid domination system,

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:22.760 align:middle line:84%
the ideals of fealty,
obedience-- right?

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:23.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:26.530 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And then we started
to talk about equality,

00:41:26.530 --> 00:41:28.030 align:middle line:90%
about democracy.

00:41:28.030 --> 00:41:28.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:29.020 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:41:29.020 --> 00:41:31.644 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But we have to be very
careful, because like freedom.

00:41:31.644 --> 00:41:35.650 align:middle line:84%
Freedom is used by the
corporate interests that

00:41:35.650 --> 00:41:38.960 align:middle line:84%
don't want regulation as
freedom for those on top

00:41:38.960 --> 00:41:40.007 align:middle line:90%
to do whatever they want.

00:41:40.007 --> 00:41:40.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:41:40.590 --> 00:41:42.774 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And the same
thing in families.

00:41:42.774 --> 00:41:44.440 align:middle line:84%
You know, the family
is supposed to have

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:46.280 align:middle line:90%
freedom from interference.

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:49.080 align:middle line:84%
But what that really means
in a dominator family

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:50.580 align:middle line:90%
is that kids can be abused.

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:52.260 align:middle line:90%
Women can be abused.

00:41:52.260 --> 00:41:54.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's only as we move
to the partnership side

00:41:54.490 --> 00:41:56.450 align:middle line:84%
that you see the reporting
of spousal abuse.

00:41:56.450 --> 00:41:57.860 align:middle line:90%
Do you see what I'm saying?

00:41:57.860 --> 00:41:59.850 align:middle line:84%
It's not that
there's more of it.

00:41:59.850 --> 00:42:03.460 align:middle line:84%
It's that people are coming
out with it because we're

00:42:03.460 --> 00:42:04.865 align:middle line:90%
moving to the partnership side.

00:42:04.865 --> 00:42:07.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And we're also doing
that in an economics way.

00:42:07.240 --> 00:42:09.940 align:middle line:84%
There's an old economic
map and a new economic map

00:42:09.940 --> 00:42:12.090 align:middle line:84%
here, that your organization
also talks about.

00:42:12.090 --> 00:42:15.080 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, that comes from
"The Real Wealth of Nations."

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:20.210 align:middle line:84%
Because the old economic map
really only included the market

00:42:20.210 --> 00:42:23.950 align:middle line:84%
economy, the government economy,
and the illegal economy.

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:27.425 align:middle line:84%
But it left out, as I said, when
we were talking about measures,

00:42:27.425 --> 00:42:30.280 align:middle line:84%
the three
life-sustaining sectors.

00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:33.610 align:middle line:84%
And we have got
to include those.

00:42:33.610 --> 00:42:37.330 align:middle line:84%
We have to have these social
wealth economic measurements.

00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And I really want to
invite our viewers

00:42:40.910 --> 00:42:46.640 align:middle line:84%
to become engaged in this, to
really take our Caring Economy

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:48.740 align:middle line:90%
online leadership program.

00:42:48.740 --> 00:42:51.900 align:middle line:84%
Because as the
former teacher said,

00:42:51.900 --> 00:42:54.410 align:middle line:84%
how do we make
social change happen?

00:42:54.410 --> 00:42:56.830 align:middle line:84%
We can't just do it
by deconstruction.

00:42:56.830 --> 00:42:58.720 align:middle line:84%
We can't do it by
just rebelling.

00:42:58.720 --> 00:43:01.270 align:middle line:84%
We have to also show what
needs to be reconstructed.

00:43:01.270 --> 00:43:05.250 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So we have to move
from this domination model

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:07.007 align:middle line:84%
more towards a
partnership model.

00:43:07.007 --> 00:43:07.590 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yes.

00:43:07.590 --> 00:43:09.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We have to
find a way where

00:43:09.470 --> 00:43:13.860 align:middle line:84%
we can create this social
and cultural transformation.

00:43:13.860 --> 00:43:15.680 align:middle line:90%
But we have to do it how?

00:43:15.680 --> 00:43:17.320 align:middle line:90%
Specifically how do we do this?

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:20.910 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, if you want
to change the economic system,

00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:27.400 align:middle line:84%
as I said, these are the steps
that we are talking about.

00:43:27.400 --> 00:43:30.960 align:middle line:84%
You have to start talking
about a caring economy.

00:43:30.960 --> 00:43:32.820 align:middle line:84%
And when people
do a double take,

00:43:32.820 --> 00:43:36.290 align:middle line:84%
you remind them that
that reaction really

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:39.260 align:middle line:84%
shows how brainwashed
we've been,

00:43:39.260 --> 00:43:44.180 align:middle line:84%
to accept a system guided
by uncaring values.

00:43:44.180 --> 00:43:47.000 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, there are
some very specific steps.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:50.420 align:middle line:84%
Raising the status of women, as
you saw in the Nordic nations,

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:52.796 align:middle line:90%
leads to more caring policies.

00:43:52.796 --> 00:43:54.170 align:middle line:84%
When you're dealing
with systems,

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:55.420 align:middle line:90%
you have to connect the dots.

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:57.360 align:middle line:90%
It's interactive.

00:43:57.360 --> 00:43:59.260 align:middle line:90%
It isn't just one thing.

00:43:59.260 --> 00:44:01.590 align:middle line:84%
So wherever you happen
to be-- but see,

00:44:01.590 --> 00:44:04.540 align:middle line:84%
the reason that these
Nordic nations moved more

00:44:04.540 --> 00:44:07.760 align:middle line:84%
to a caring economy is
because they moved more

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:11.560 align:middle line:84%
from a domination to
a partnership system.

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:14.360 align:middle line:84%
They have more
democracy and equality

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:17.360 align:middle line:84%
in both the family
and the state.

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:20.200 align:middle line:84%
They are trying to
leave behind what

00:44:20.200 --> 00:44:22.860 align:middle line:90%
keeps domination systems going.

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:24.330 align:middle line:90%
Fear, force.

00:44:24.330 --> 00:44:27.520 align:middle line:84%
The first peace studies,
the first laws--

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:31.110 align:middle line:84%
that it's illegal to use
physical punishment of children

00:44:31.110 --> 00:44:32.450 align:middle line:90%
in families.

00:44:32.450 --> 00:44:34.840 align:middle line:84%
Men's movement to
disentangle masculinity

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:37.880 align:middle line:84%
from its association with
domination and violence.

00:44:37.880 --> 00:44:41.330 align:middle line:84%
And yes, a much more
equal partnership

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:43.330 align:middle line:90%
between women and men.

00:44:43.330 --> 00:44:47.090 align:middle line:84%
And so, as the
status of women rose,

00:44:47.090 --> 00:44:51.630 align:middle line:84%
men no longer found it such
a threat to their status,

00:44:51.630 --> 00:44:54.590 align:middle line:84%
to their quote,
masculinity, to really

00:44:54.590 --> 00:44:57.280 align:middle line:90%
also embrace more caring values.

00:44:57.280 --> 00:44:58.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is a great point.

00:44:58.870 --> 00:45:00.530 align:middle line:84%
I mean, can we
talk about the men?

00:45:00.530 --> 00:45:02.300 align:middle line:84%
Can we talk about the
fact that maybe they

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:05.910 align:middle line:84%
don't want to bear all
that responsibility.

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they want to
share the parenting

00:45:08.570 --> 00:45:10.550 align:middle line:84%
and be more part of
their children's lives.

00:45:10.550 --> 00:45:12.880 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they want to have
a dual-income family.

00:45:12.880 --> 00:45:15.125 align:middle line:84%
Maybe this is something
that is desired.

00:45:15.125 --> 00:45:16.900 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well, it's two ways.

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:19.290 align:middle line:84%
We're always back to the
personal and the social.

00:45:19.290 --> 00:45:19.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:45:19.790 --> 00:45:20.510 align:middle line:90%
True.

00:45:20.510 --> 00:45:20.790 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:45:20.790 --> 00:45:22.340 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Because
the only reason

00:45:22.340 --> 00:45:26.560 align:middle line:84%
that we are-- that more men
are doing the parenting,

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:27.600 align:middle line:90%
the mothering-- is

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:29.391 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is because the
mothers are working.

00:45:29.391 --> 00:45:30.190 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well, no.

00:45:30.190 --> 00:45:34.834 align:middle line:84%
It's actually because
it's no longer such a--

00:45:34.834 --> 00:45:36.304 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, unacceptable thing.

00:45:36.304 --> 00:45:37.970 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --unacceptable
thing for a man

00:45:37.970 --> 00:45:40.460 align:middle line:84%
to do, to diaper a
baby or to feed a baby.

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:41.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:45:41.170 --> 00:45:43.720 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: You know, women
going into the workplace

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:46.790 align:middle line:84%
has really, in many ways, been
a very important influence

00:45:46.790 --> 00:45:49.320 align:middle line:90%
in humanizing the workplace.

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:50.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Explain that.

00:45:50.530 --> 00:45:51.890 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well, yes.

00:45:51.890 --> 00:45:57.690 align:middle line:84%
I mean, all the way from not
such austere surroundings

00:45:57.690 --> 00:46:03.230 align:middle line:84%
to the movement towards
child care, towards--

00:46:03.230 --> 00:46:04.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Partnership.

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:06.400 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Towards partnership.

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:09.530 align:middle line:84%
And also the movement
towards, really,

00:46:09.530 --> 00:46:12.360 align:middle line:84%
more caring and
nurturing leadership

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:14.100 align:middle line:90%
styles, which we are learning.

00:46:14.100 --> 00:46:15.510 align:middle line:90%
I teach leadership.

00:46:15.510 --> 00:46:16.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Thank goodness.

00:46:16.840 --> 00:46:21.530 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: The leader
that elicits from others

00:46:21.530 --> 00:46:23.620 align:middle line:84%
their highest
potentials-- what I

00:46:23.620 --> 00:46:25.670 align:middle line:84%
call in a hierarchy
of actualization

00:46:25.670 --> 00:46:29.147 align:middle line:84%
rather than domination--
gets the best results.

00:46:29.147 --> 00:46:29.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's true.

00:46:29.980 --> 00:46:35.340 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And so this movement
towards a more partnership

00:46:35.340 --> 00:46:38.270 align:middle line:84%
has a lot to do with the
changing of the gender roles

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:39.130 align:middle line:90%
and relations.

00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:40.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:46:40.230 --> 00:46:41.250 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:43.660 align:middle line:84%
When we talk about
a caring economy,

00:46:43.660 --> 00:46:46.780 align:middle line:84%
there's a clip that comes from
the DVD "Tomorrow's Children"

00:46:46.780 --> 00:46:49.990 align:middle line:84%
where Riane talks about--
specifically talks about what

00:46:49.990 --> 00:46:51.430 align:middle line:90%
a caring economy is.

00:46:51.430 --> 00:46:53.020 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look.

00:46:53.020 --> 00:46:54.820 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:46:54.820 --> 00:46:57.570 align:middle line:84%
--Now, you've probably
noticed that just

00:46:57.570 --> 00:47:01.040 align:middle line:84%
hearing "caring" and "economics"
in the same sentence,

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:03.790 align:middle line:84%
people tend to do a
double take, don't they?

00:47:03.790 --> 00:47:04.820 align:middle line:90%
But think about it.

00:47:04.820 --> 00:47:10.530 align:middle line:84%
Isn't that a terrible comment
on the uncaring values

00:47:10.530 --> 00:47:14.710 align:middle line:84%
we've learned to take
for granted as driving

00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:17.010 align:middle line:90%
economic systems?

00:47:17.010 --> 00:47:20.850 align:middle line:84%
We wouldn't have our
environmental, social,

00:47:20.850 --> 00:47:25.540 align:middle line:84%
and economic crises, global
warming, chronic hunger

00:47:25.540 --> 00:47:31.670 align:middle line:84%
and poverty, if we had more
caring economic systems.

00:47:31.670 --> 00:47:35.060 align:middle line:84%
But it is today more
urgent than ever

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:40.710 align:middle line:84%
before that we shift to,
yes, to a caring economics.

00:47:40.710 --> 00:47:44.680 align:middle line:84%
Because we are in
the midst of a major,

00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:47.940 align:middle line:84%
major technological
and economic and social

00:47:47.940 --> 00:47:53.280 align:middle line:84%
shift-- the shift into the
post-industrial service

00:47:53.280 --> 00:47:56.040 align:middle line:90%
information economy.

00:47:56.040 --> 00:48:00.370 align:middle line:84%
A time of seismic
technological changes,

00:48:00.370 --> 00:48:06.070 align:middle line:84%
when manufacturing and other
jobs are being eliminated

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:10.460 align:middle line:84%
by not just automation, but
at an ever more rapid clip

00:48:10.460 --> 00:48:11.940 align:middle line:90%
by robotics.

00:48:11.940 --> 00:48:15.300 align:middle line:84%
A time when
economists never tire

00:48:15.300 --> 00:48:20.480 align:middle line:84%
of telling us that the most
important capital-- yes, they

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:25.520 align:middle line:84%
call it capital-- for a
successful post-industrial era

00:48:25.520 --> 00:48:29.620 align:middle line:84%
is what they call high
quality, human capital.

00:48:29.620 --> 00:48:30.610 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:35.100 align:middle line:84%
That is flexible,
innovative, creative people,

00:48:35.100 --> 00:48:38.040 align:middle line:84%
people with highly
developed capacities.

00:48:38.040 --> 00:48:40.310 align:middle line:84%
But consider that
these capacities

00:48:40.310 --> 00:48:43.000 align:middle line:84%
aren't just developed in
universities, as important

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:44.250 align:middle line:90%
as that is.

00:48:44.250 --> 00:48:49.320 align:middle line:84%
Whether or not these capacities
are or are not developed,

00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:51.940 align:middle line:84%
we now know-- not
only from psychology

00:48:51.940 --> 00:48:57.620 align:middle line:84%
but from neuroscience--
depends to a huge extent

00:48:57.620 --> 00:49:02.940 align:middle line:84%
on the quality of
care children receive.

00:49:02.940 --> 00:49:07.730 align:middle line:84%
So yes, this is the
time to move forward.

00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:08.996 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:49:08.996 --> 00:49:10.370 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I want
to say something

00:49:10.370 --> 00:49:12.640 align:middle line:90%
very quickly about poverty.

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:14.430 align:middle line:84%
Because the mass
of the world's poor

00:49:14.430 --> 00:49:16.670 align:middle line:84%
and the poorest of
the poor are women.

00:49:16.670 --> 00:49:19.310 align:middle line:84%
Women in this country
over the age of 65,

00:49:19.310 --> 00:49:22.270 align:middle line:84%
according to the US
Census, are twice as

00:49:22.270 --> 00:49:24.740 align:middle line:84%
likely to be poor as
men of the same age.

00:49:24.740 --> 00:49:26.880 align:middle line:84%
And that's not only
job discrimination,

00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:30.860 align:middle line:84%
that's because most of them
are or were either full or part

00:49:30.860 --> 00:49:31.980 align:middle line:90%
time caregivers.

00:49:31.980 --> 00:49:33.880 align:middle line:90%
And poverty is their reward.

00:49:33.880 --> 00:49:36.360 align:middle line:84%
If we're serious
about less poverty,

00:49:36.360 --> 00:49:40.560 align:middle line:84%
we have to move to a caring
economy that gives visibility

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:44.005 align:middle line:84%
and real value to this
most essential human work.

00:49:44.005 --> 00:49:45.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I remember
you telling me

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:46.838 align:middle line:84%
in one of the past--
the radio show

00:49:46.838 --> 00:49:50.620 align:middle line:84%
interviews I did with you
about Salary.com did a survey

00:49:50.620 --> 00:49:54.240 align:middle line:84%
and decided that the average
salary of a working mother

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:57.960 align:middle line:84%
would be something
like $234,000 a year,

00:49:57.960 --> 00:50:01.450 align:middle line:84%
based on the amount of
hours they put in working

00:50:01.450 --> 00:50:03.750 align:middle line:84%
as a stay-at-home
mom, essentially.

00:50:03.750 --> 00:50:04.590 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well, we-

00:50:04.590 --> 00:50:05.506 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --as a mother.

00:50:05.506 --> 00:50:08.220 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And yet economists
talk about stay-at-home mothers

00:50:08.220 --> 00:50:11.090 align:middle line:84%
and fathers as
economically unproductive.

00:50:11.090 --> 00:50:11.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ugh.

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:14.940 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: So we've got to change
the whole way of thinking.

00:50:14.940 --> 00:50:18.440 align:middle line:84%
What is really the-- One
of the pivotal questions

00:50:18.440 --> 00:50:20.500 align:middle line:84%
for this post-industrial
era, when

00:50:20.500 --> 00:50:22.830 align:middle line:84%
robotics as I said--
And by the way,

00:50:22.830 --> 00:50:28.310 align:middle line:84%
that clip is from our PowerPoint
for the Caring Economy

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:30.990 align:middle line:84%
training, that people
get ahold of when

00:50:30.990 --> 00:50:33.080 align:middle line:90%
they take the online training.

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:33.890 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you can see
more of that there.

00:50:33.890 --> 00:50:34.240 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:50:34.240 --> 00:50:34.865 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yeah.

00:50:34.865 --> 00:50:37.960 align:middle line:84%
So they get a whole
panoply of materials.

00:50:37.960 --> 00:50:40.710 align:middle line:84%
But I mean, the whole
point of it is, look.

00:50:40.710 --> 00:50:43.640 align:middle line:84%
It's caused a lot of
suffering in the past.

00:50:43.640 --> 00:50:45.620 align:middle line:84%
It will continue to
cause a lot of suffering.

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:49.675 align:middle line:84%
But we're at a place where
we had better move there now.

00:50:49.675 --> 00:50:50.385 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:50:50.385 --> 00:50:52.010 align:middle line:84%
Actually, one of the
Facebook questions

00:50:52.010 --> 00:50:54.090 align:middle line:84%
that's coming in from
Tina is basically

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:57.860 align:middle line:84%
saying that the domination model
has gotten so fierce right now.

00:50:57.860 --> 00:50:59.650 align:middle line:90%
Is this a last stand?

00:50:59.650 --> 00:51:03.620 align:middle line:84%
Is this something that
is maybe the end, because

00:51:03.620 --> 00:51:05.580 align:middle line:84%
of its fierceness,
at this point?

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:09.270 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, we would like to
think that, but I'm afraid not.

00:51:09.270 --> 00:51:12.150 align:middle line:84%
Because what we see
in modern history

00:51:12.150 --> 00:51:14.990 align:middle line:84%
is that, since moving
from the Middle Ages

00:51:14.990 --> 00:51:18.450 align:middle line:84%
to today, where we have much
more partnership elements,

00:51:18.450 --> 00:51:20.360 align:middle line:84%
is all the progressive
movements have

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:21.860 align:middle line:84%
challenged traditions
of domination.

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:24.900 align:middle line:84%
You know, divinely ordained
right of kings to rule.

00:51:24.900 --> 00:51:27.020 align:middle line:84%
Divinely ordained
right of men to rule

00:51:27.020 --> 00:51:28.070 align:middle line:90%
over women and children.

00:51:28.070 --> 00:51:30.760 align:middle line:84%
Divinely ordained right of
one race to rule another.

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:33.540 align:middle line:84%
All the way to man's
once-hallowed conquest

00:51:33.540 --> 00:51:34.080 align:middle line:90%
of nature.

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:35.310 align:middle line:84%
You know, the right
to exploit, et cetera.

00:51:35.310 --> 00:51:36.185 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:51:36.185 --> 00:51:37.940 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But all
of this has been

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:41.190 align:middle line:84%
more of a spiral upward
movement with dips.

00:51:41.190 --> 00:51:44.140 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
that we can be sure

00:51:44.140 --> 00:51:48.340 align:middle line:84%
that there won't be anymore dips
is if we build the foundations.

00:51:48.340 --> 00:51:50.930 align:middle line:84%
And the foundations
have to do with what

00:51:50.930 --> 00:51:52.640 align:middle line:90%
we've been talking about.

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:55.180 align:middle line:90%
How are children brought up?

00:51:55.180 --> 00:51:58.440 align:middle line:84%
Is it in dominator or
partnership styles?

00:51:58.440 --> 00:52:00.420 align:middle line:84%
That's why the Caring
and Connected Parenting

00:52:00.420 --> 00:52:02.520 align:middle line:90%
Guide we have is so important.

00:52:02.520 --> 00:52:05.980 align:middle line:84%
What is the relationship between
the two halves of humanity,

00:52:05.980 --> 00:52:08.830 align:middle line:84%
that children observe, which
is a model for all relations?

00:52:08.830 --> 00:52:09.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Men and women.

00:52:09.770 --> 00:52:11.230 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Men and women.

00:52:11.230 --> 00:52:15.330 align:middle line:90%
And some basics, like economics.

00:52:15.330 --> 00:52:16.800 align:middle line:90%
What do we reward?

00:52:16.800 --> 00:52:19.085 align:middle line:84%
What do we consider
valuable work?

00:52:19.085 --> 00:52:22.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And there's
actually a great clip

00:52:22.720 --> 00:52:24.320 align:middle line:90%
that you quote Margaret Mead.

00:52:24.320 --> 00:52:26.620 align:middle line:84%
And she offers a
wonderful suggestion

00:52:26.620 --> 00:52:29.677 align:middle line:84%
on how we could really create
change by working together.

00:52:29.677 --> 00:52:30.510 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:52:30.510 --> 00:52:32.950 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:52:32.950 --> 00:52:36.010 align:middle line:84%
--I want to close
by reminding us

00:52:36.010 --> 00:52:39.030 align:middle line:84%
of something that
Margaret Mead pointed out.

00:52:39.030 --> 00:52:43.670 align:middle line:84%
That the only thing that ever
brought about positive change

00:52:43.670 --> 00:52:47.400 align:middle line:84%
is a group of dedicated
women and men.

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:51.780 align:middle line:84%
So let's be that group of
dedicated women and men.

00:52:51.780 --> 00:52:57.160 align:middle line:84%
Let's join together to
really make that difference,

00:52:57.160 --> 00:53:02.810 align:middle line:84%
to send a steady stream of
pressure and information,

00:53:02.810 --> 00:53:08.510 align:middle line:84%
and yes, new thinking to our
policymakers, to our neighbors,

00:53:08.510 --> 00:53:12.750 align:middle line:84%
to our friends, to everyone
in our sphere of influence.

00:53:12.750 --> 00:53:16.430 align:middle line:84%
Let's do what we
need to do to move

00:53:16.430 --> 00:53:21.190 align:middle line:84%
to that economic system
that is so urgently needed

00:53:21.190 --> 00:53:24.420 align:middle line:84%
at this critical time
in human history.

00:53:24.420 --> 00:53:27.910 align:middle line:84%
An economic system that
gives visibility and value

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:31.920 align:middle line:84%
to the most important human
work: the work of caring

00:53:31.920 --> 00:53:34.920 align:middle line:84%
for people starting in
childhood and caring

00:53:34.920 --> 00:53:36.880 align:middle line:90%
for our mother Earth.

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:40.460 align:middle line:84%
So I invite you to
join me and the Center

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:44.540 align:middle line:84%
for Partnership Studies in
this exciting and urgently

00:53:44.540 --> 00:53:46.140 align:middle line:90%
needed enterprise.

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:47.290 align:middle line:90%
Let's do it.

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:50.440 align:middle line:84%
Let's do it for ourselves,
for our children,

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:52.750 align:middle line:90%
and for generations to come.

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:53.530 align:middle line:90%
I thank you.

